c) does not necessarily follow a) + b) here<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->No, the issue is that<br>
a) because the mob drops 72 keys everytime, and<br>
b) because you can also quest the key<br>
c) then the mob doesn't require rotation and, therefore, no rules.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Yes, folks say &quot;it's only for this mob&quot; - famous last words.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->The only person I see extrapolating anything is ...well ...you.  If this is such a concern for you ...rotate all of the other PoP mobs that offer flags, but who do not offer an alternative means of questing for that flag (as was suggested by Sladen).  This is a reasonable compromise that most people are willing to live with.  Aerin'Dar, Grummus, Behemoth would remain FFA and teamable ...while every other PoP flag mob can be governed by RTA rotation rules (non-teamable) and you can be their Lord and Master.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The first &quot;official&quot; rotation was Trakanon. When Talendor was killed, the rules for the Trakanon rotation were extrapolated to extend to Talendor (basically it was search-n-replace &quot;Trakanon&quot; with &quot;Talendor&quot; and *poof* you have the new rules).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Putting the chicken before the egg again?  You should say,&quot;...when Talendor was placed on rotation, he inherited the rules that governed the previous Trakanon rotation...&quot; other wise you completely miss the point.  The difference here is that you are attempting to give rotation rules to a mob that is not on rotation.  No one is arguing that, should a rotation be set up for AD, what the rules would be when that occurs ...we assume that he will inherit the same rules as all other rotation governed mobs.  The argument is whether or not AD NEEDS TO BE ON ROTATION AT ALL.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>If you cannot see our side of the argument then we are at an impass. I assure you that we see yours and take it into consideration when we form our opinion on the matter. You need to convince me (and others) that this isn't simply a foot in the door. I will say that the qualification (similar to what has been given already) of something like:<br>
<br>
&quot;Mobs that enable entry into further zones when killed - whether by dropping an item which enables entry either directly or by completing a quest for such a key, giving character flags, or by any other means not specifically mentioned here - that can also be bypassed by quests that provide an alternate path to entry to the further zones but the quest does not require killing said mob to complete the alternate-path quest, which also have been proven to not stir any interest because of other items that they may drop and, because of this, have been proven to remain &quot;up&quot; for long periods of time, are open to FFA rules.&quot;<br>
<br>
is a little better.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Did you write this or just throw it up on a piece of paper?  Can you translate for me what it says?  I think you are making this entirely too difficult.<br>
<br>
First, since when has any RTA rule been written in such a purposefully confusing way?  Me thinks you doth jest, otherwise you have completely and utterly lost sight of the topic of this conversation and I would truly have to question whether you see 'our' side or not.<br>
<br>
Second, since when does the RTA make rules for FFA mobs?  We don't have a rule that says &quot; blah blah blah ...Gorenaire is open to FFA rules&quot;, do we?  What, exactly ARE FFA rules anyways?  How can anyone enforce &quot;Free For All&quot;?  lol<br>
<br>
The RTA doesn't need to do anything ...period, zip, zilch, nada.  Let's face it, by your own admission, you do not care if an FFA mob is teamed.  Currently, Aerin'Dar, Behemoth, and Grummus are all FFA ...hence they can be teamed for the purpose of flagging.  No amount of whining and crying here on the RTA boards can make that any less of a fact than it already is.  However, to address your concern that this 'precedence' is not carried over (on purpose or by accident) to all other PoP flag mobs (and therefore, be able to team all the way up the ladder), then it would be advisable that you place all the other PoP flag mobs on their own separate rotations.  Once on rotation, those other PoP flag mobs will inherit the rules and established written conventions of all other rotation mobs ...i.e. alliance rules.  Problem is solved.<br>
<br>
Does it get any simpler than that?  We have a workable compromise ...concerns from both sides are covered ...most everyone is happy (minus those people who are wanting to put AD on rotation for the sole purpose of denying access and content to other guilds ...they won't be too happy, I'd guess).<br>
