And this is complete supposition on your part.  I've stated repeatedly what I think about it and this is not it.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>No, the issue is that<br>
a) because the mob drops 72 keys everytime, and<br>
b) because you can also quest the key<br>
c) then the mob doesn't require rotation and, therefore, no rules.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
a) and b) do not derive c) here.  The mob may have amazing items that are even better than access to other areas and everybody wants the items - thus requiring a rotation, something that has been failed to be addressed yet again.  Remember, I am NOT talking about AD or whoever you choose to use as your example.  I'm talking in general -- maybe some future mob down the line.<br>
<br>
I think what you want is:<br>
<br>
Concerning Aerin Dar:<br>
a) Because the mob drops keys everytime (the number is no consequence) to grant access to another zone,<br>
b) Because you can also quest a key to give access to this same other zone,<br>
c) Because the items that the mob drops are of no consequence to anyone (although this is quite subjective),<br>
d) As evicence of a), b), and c) there has been no contention for this mob as of yet as evidenced by the fact that no formal request for rotation on these mobs has been offered to-date by anyone,<br>
e) Then the mob doesn't require rotation and, therefore, no rules, which allow teaming up on the mob in any form desired.<br>
f) However, it may be in the future that a rotation needs to be in effect on this mob, if contention increases to the point some guild/group requests it.<br>
<br>
Then, this can be similarly applied (or inherited if you like) by any other mob having similar properties in the future.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The only person I see extrapolating anything is ...well ...you. If this is such a concern for you ...rotate all of the other PoP mobs that offer flags, but who do not offer an alternative means of questing for that flag (as was suggested by Sladen). This is a reasonable compromise that most people are willing to live with. Aerin'Dar, Grummus, Behemoth would remain FFA and teamable ...while every other PoP flag mob can be governed by RTA rotation rules (non-teamable) and you can be their Lord and Master.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Idiotic rhetoric aside, I personally have no problem with the compromise either, as I've stated many times.  I've stated my concerns repeatedly and they aren't about ownership of anything.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Putting the chicken before the egg again? You should say,&quot;...when Talendor was placed on rotation, he inherited the rules that governed the previous Trakanon rotation...&quot; other wise you completely miss the point. The difference here is that you are attempting to give rotation rules to a mob that is not on rotation. No one is arguing that, should a rotation be set up for AD, what the rules would be when that occurs ...we assume that he will inherit the same rules as all other rotation governed mobs. The argument is whether or not AD NEEDS TO BE ON ROTATION AT ALL.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I disagree.  Although no one had killed Talendor ever, the guild that killed Talendor did go by the rules as if the mob had been on rotation.  That is, they did not get every guild on the server together and kill it, then say that we have to all do it as seperate guilds.  They EXTRAPOLATED the rotation rules to Talendor and killed Talendor as if it had been on rotation (they killed it with only their guild, no teaming) and continued to kill it as such until another guild also killed it as if it had been on rotation (only their guild, no teaming, etc) and then established a rotation INHERITING the rules from Trakanon.<br>
<br>
Again, my discussion has nothing to do with AD.  It is about precedent and clarity.  I don't care if you are talking about AD or Emperor Crush.  The mob name in question is simply circumstantial.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Did you write this or just throw it up on a piece of paper? Can you translate for me what it says? I think you are making this entirely too difficult.<br>
<br>
First, since when has any RTA rule been written in such a purposefully confusing way? Me thinks you doth jest, otherwise you have completely and utterly lost sight of the topic of this conversation and I would truly have to question whether you see 'our' side or not.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I wrote it on the fly.  It was somewhat tongue-in-cheek but I wanted to show that you need to nail down the qualifications and not just gloss over it or someone in the future (probably about 8 months from now if history is any indicator) would simply say &quot;MobX is done this way, why isn't MobY&quot; and no one would know why there is a difference.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Second, since when does the RTA make rules for FFA mobs? We don't have a rule that says &quot; blah blah blah ...Gorenaire is open to FFA rules&quot;, do we? What, exactly ARE FFA rules anyways? How can anyone enforce &quot;Free For All&quot;? lol<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
See the above text on extrapolation vs. inheritance.  FFA means that there are no rules, even to the point of multiple simultaneous engagements are allowed and the killing blow wins it.  Most prefer the term FCFS (first come, first served).<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The RTA doesn't need to do anything ...period, zip, zilch, nada. Let's face it, by your own admission, you do not care if an FFA mob is teamed. Currently, Aerin'Dar, Behemoth, and Grummus are all FFA <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, this is where you are wrong.  The point that I (and others) are trying to make have nothing to do with any particular mob.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>However, to address your concern that this 'precedence' is not carried over (on purpose or by accident) to all other PoP flag mobs (and therefore, be able to team all the way up the ladder), then it would be advisable that you place all the other PoP flag mobs on their own separate rotations. Once on rotation, those other PoP flag mobs will inherit the rules and established written conventions of all other rotation mobs ...i.e. alliance rules. Problem is solved.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That may solve the &quot;how&quot; but not the &quot;why&quot;.  You have set up no qualifications as to why those mobs are treated differently that are convincing.  Above I give you your out.<br>
<br>
Again, I have no problem with AD/Grummus/Behemoth being FFA even provided there are clear and concise reasons why they are allowed to be whatever they are and how they are different from every other case in the game and why that warrants the difference in treatment.  I have convinced myself why they are OK to be FCFS and how to differentiate between any future mobs so that creep doesn't destroy valid rotations a while back.  I've given you the criteria to convince me above, without using leaps of faith instead of logic. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eqashke>EQAshke</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(4/9/03 5:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm50.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=646.topic&index=165>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_smile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Response to Teamwork thread in guild rep forum.  </span><hr size=1> Thank you, Gromm for finally including a solution to something in one of your long winded answers.  This makes sense:<br>
