<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.drow.org" target="top">Blood of the Spider</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#222222><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=thundaxstormkeeper>Thundax Stormkeeper</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(4/10/03 8:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm50.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=646.topic&index=176>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_smile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Response to Teamwork thread in guild rep forum.  </span><hr size=1> What specifics of a rotational mob you have never encountered, let alone killed would necessitate the guilds who have killed it to ask for your input on?<br>
<br>
The community as a whole is more than welcome to talk about and propose general rules regarding rotations or server rules or whatever else, but rotation rules should always be determined by the guilds that are on a rotation.<br>
<br>
A guild that joins a rotation is more than welcome to have input into the rules of that rotation and ask the guilds involved to vote on it, but why should you vote on that rotation if you have nothing to do with it.<br>
<br>
Are you going to suggest the amount of time a guild should have to clear Vex Thal when they are up for it? Or which mob counts as giving rotational access to Vex Thal?<br>
<br>
The entire idea of joining a rotation is that you are breaking into that rotation. Now in most circumstances, many guilds are willing to give a guild who asks a shot at the mob, but in some cases they may not. This is where racing to that mob may be necessary. You don't have the right to call for a rule change to a rotational mob just because it might make it easier for you to join that rotation.<br>
<br>
There is absolutely no logic in asking for a vote by the guilds of the server each time a new rotation is set up. The majority of the guilds would be voting on issues they knew nothing about. If an issue affects two or three guilds only, then why would it be necessary for twenty guilds to vote on it? Seems slightly absurd to me.<br>
<br>
There is absolutely no way to argue that having rotations slows down the progress of up and coming guilds. As has been stated thousands of times before, rotations give guilds who are capable of killing a mob a guaranteed chance to kill that mob every x amount of time. If there were no rotations then sure, some guilds might get to kill one mob more often, but they would also probably lose out on other mobs that they wanted to kill.<br>
<br>
What you currently see is that when a guild decides a rotation is no longer valuable to them, they move to autopass on it. This means there are more kills available to the guilds still on the rotation, as well as new ones joining it. However, if there were no rotation rules, it is quite likely that many rotation mobs would get killed by small groups of people in big guilds whenever they found them up to equip alts or make cash etc.<br>
<br>
Many people seem to cry foul of the bigger guilds who are supposedly stifling their chance to grow and access new content. It is not logical to argue that BotS was able to do so well because they got to kill content with no competition for so long, and thus because of rotations, smaller guilds can no longer able to grow as fast because of this. Surely everyone can see that the prize of working hard and getting there first is to have little or no competition on content. It has always been the case in EQ that if you are ahead of the curve you will have more opportunities than those below you.<br>
<br>
This thread has nothing to do with people saying that what CB and VoLS did was against the rules. It wasn't, and that is exactly what this thread is about. Most of those who have killed Aerin`Dar by themselves are not happy with the situation of guilds teaming up on non rotation mobs then killing their rotation mobs as seperate entities. The idea here is to try and establish a set of rules that is fair for everyone and doesn't create any double standards as currently exist.<br>
<br>
Thun <p>Thundax Stormkeeper<br>
Warder of the Rathe<br>
