<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is absolutely no logic in asking for a vote by the guilds of the server each time a new rotation is set up. The majority of the guilds would be voting on issues they knew nothing about. If an issue affects two or three guilds only, then why would it be necessary for twenty guilds to vote on it? Seems slightly absurd to me.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Because ...maybe ...just maybe ...the other guilds might want to have a say in their future?  Naaa... that's silly.  Why would any other guild want to have a voice in their future when you are doing so well in looking out for us and always making sure that we aren't hampered in any way?  Hey!  I have an idea!  The next time there is an abortion bill introduced, lets only let women who have HAD abortions vote! ...truly, they are the only ones who know what they are talking about.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>There is absolutely no way to argue that having rotations slows down the progress of up and coming guilds. As has been stated thousands of times before, rotations give guilds who are capable of killing a mob a guaranteed chance to kill that mob every x amount of time. If there were no rotations then sure, some guilds might get to kill one mob more often, but they would also probably lose out on other mobs that they wanted to kill.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->1001 now ...and it still has nothing to do with the discussion of Aerin'Dar, Grummus, and Behemoth who are not currently on rotation.  I would have thought after 1000 times, it would mean something by now ...hmm ...guess not.  *shrug*<br>
<br>
...and I think I have previously made a very clear and logical argument using rotations (of Aerin'Dar, Grummus, and Behemoth) as a means to slow down the progression of up and coming guilds.  I've made the argument several times ...should be hard for you to find. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What you currently see is that when a guild decides a rotation is no longer valuable to them, they move to autopass on it. This means there are more kills available to the guilds still on the rotation, as well as new ones joining it. However, if there were no rotation rules, it is quite likely that many rotation mobs would get killed by small groups of people in big guilds whenever they found them up to equip alts or make cash etc.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->...and we are back to assuming that any questioning of the RTA rules means that you automatically want to go to an FFA server.  *sigh* DING! You have increased your level to 66 of completely ignoring everything being said up to this point!  Gratz!  Wtg!<br>
